You can use the MENU statement to define a menu. Then, you can add items to this menu using the ADD ITEM clause. For example:
```4gl
MENU("File")
ADD ITEM(NAME="Open");
ADD ITEM(TYPE=MENU_ITEM);
ADD MENU_POPUP(TITLE="About");
DISPLAY(TITLE:"File Menu");
```
This code creates an "File" menu and adds two items to it. The first item is called 'Open' and its data type is set to MENU_ITEM. Its submenu is set to 'About', which will display the title 'About' when you click on it. Then, the form is displayed with the title "File Menu". You can now use this menu in your code, such as performing actions with its items or setting their values.

You can define a function in Actian 4GL with any desired signature, including one that accepts an array of integers as its argument. Here's an example of how to create a function that calculates the sum of its integer arguments:
```4gl
FUNCTION ADD_NUMBERS(a INTEGER)
    FIELD a = NULL;
    FOR i IN 1 TO a.SIZE
        FIELD i = a[i];
    SUM(fi) = 0;
    WHILE (fi > 0)
        SUM(fi) += fi;
    RETURN SUM(fi);
END FUNCTION
```
This code defines an 'ADD_NUMBERS' function that takes a single integer argument and stores it in the 'a' field. Then, it loops through all the elements of the array using the 'FOR' clause. Inside the loop, it accesses each element 'i' and adds its value to the 'SUM(fi)' variable. Finally, when the loop terminates, the function returns the final sum in the 'SUM(fi)' variable. You can then call this function from your code by specifying its name followed by an integer argument enclosed in parentheses:
```4gl
CALL ADD_NUMBERS(10);
```
This code calls the 'ADD_NUMBERS' function with a single integer argument of 10. Actian 4GL will then execute this statement, storing the value of 10 into the 'a' field of the function. The function will then loop through all its elements and add them up, returning the final sum in the 'SUM(fi)' variable.

You can use the FIELD statement to define a field in any object that supports fields (such as tables or objects). This statement takes two arguments: the name of the field and its initial value. For example:
```4gl
