You can define a custom class in Actian 4GL with any desired attributes and behaviors using the 'CLASS' statement. Here's an example of how to create a simple class called 'Person' that has two fields ('name' and 'age') and one method ('speak()'):
```4gl
CLASS Person
{
    FIELD name TEXT NOT NULL UNIQUE;
    FIELD age INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 18;
    METHOD speak()
        FIELD this = PERSON(name).ASSERT('not null');
        THIS.name = 'John';
        THIS.age = 35;
        WRITE($"Hello, my name is {this.name} and I am {this.age} years old.");
    END METHOD
};
```
This code defines a 'CLASS' called 'Person' with two fields ('name' and 'age'). The 'name' field is declared as a non-nullable text type, while the 'age' field is defined as an integer not nullable. Inside the class, you can see the declaration of a single method called 'speak()'. This method takes no arguments but performs some actions on itself, such as setting its own name and age attributes to specific values. Finally, when the method terminates, it writes out a message to the console that contains information about itself (its name and age). You can then create instances of this class from your code by specifying its name followed by an integer argument enclosed in parentheses:
```4gl
CALL NEW(Person);
```
This code calls the 'NEW' function with a single integer argument of 0. Actian 4GL will then create a new instance of the 'Person' class and initialize its fields with the default values specified in the class definition. The 'NEW' function also returns a reference to the newly created object, which you can then access from your code by referring to it with the '@' symbol:
```4gl
MY_PERSON = NEW(Person);
```
This statement creates a new instance of the 'Person' class and stores its reference into the 'my_person' variable. You can now use this variable in your code, such as performing calculations on it or comparing it to other values.
